We met today to keep driving forward real solutions like Ellie’s Law—the bipartisan bill I introduced to secure dedicated federal funding for brain aneurysm research. This legislation focuses on early detection, better treatment options, and the life-saving prevention strategies we desperately need.

I’m grateful to partner with such passionate advocates and was honored to receive the Brain Aneurysm Champion Award—but this work has never been about recognition. It’s about results. Name: Kim, Andy
text:
Reopening Delaney Hall won’t fix our broken immigration system or make us safer—it just pads the pockets of a private company that prioritizes profit over people.

I recently inspected an ICE detention center in New Jersey and saw how the Trump administration's claims of focusing on dangerous criminals don’t match the reality. People like Karim Daoud—who has lived here for 21 years, has no criminal record, and has a wife and kids who are U.S. citizens—are being detained. Detaining individuals like him doesn’t improve safety—it only creates division and fear in our communities.

We need transparency and accountability to be certain of safe and humane conditions at places like Delaney Hall. Most of all, we must push for real immigration reform across our nation. - AK

Deteniendo a personas como él no mejora nuestra seguridad; solo crea división y miedo en nuestras comunidades.

Since January 20, 2025, the U.S. Coast Guard has seized over 100,000 pounds of cocaine and over 10,000 pounds of marijuana, much of it trafficked through these waters.

Democrat policies have fueled this crisis. They opened our borders, defunded border enforcement, and prioritized illegal aliens and MS-13 gang members over American families. These same Democrats are now outraged over the idea of renaming a body of water that we protect, we patrol, and we pay for.

They’re not upset about geography. They’re upset because their America Last agenda is being exposed.

The Gulf of America is a symbol of national pride and it’s long past time we start acting like this is our country again.

Name: Stefanik, Elise M.
text:
Stefanik Rips Gov. Kathy Hochul’s Late, Reckless, and Disgraceful New York State Budget

Democrats and Republicans alike are rightly skewering Kathy Hochul and her budget for her sheer incompetence and catastrophic policies hurting New York. 

Governor Kathy Hochul’s disastrous $254 billion budget is not only the latest budget in over 15 years, but also it is a staggering $13 billion increase over last year’s already bloated budget and it is a double down of her failed policies that have bankrupted New York’s hardworking families. 

Under Kathy Hochul, New York already leads the nation in population loss due to unaffordability, sky-high taxes, and out-of-control crime. Hochul’s latest catastrophic budget will further exacerbate the mass exodus from our great Empire State. 

Even elected Democrats have publicly declared the budget process and outcome "shameful" and have shredded various aspects of Hochul’s budget.

Hochul puts New Yorkers last as she pours hard earned taxpayers funds into sanctuary city policies that incentivize illegal immigration all while diverting resources from our underfunded veterans’ services and law enforcement. 

Hochul once again perpetuates New York’s violent crime crisis by refusing to fully repeal disastrous bail reform laws, leaving our neighborhoods less safe and emboldening criminals. 

Her budget doubles down on insane gas stove bans and unaffordable energy regulations that will further crush families and small businesses already grappling with soaring utility bills. 

And in true NY Democrat corruption fashion, the cherry on top is Hochul’s secret taxpayer-funded slush fund for corrupt Tish James to use hard earned NYers money to defend herself in court for her illegal mortgage fraud. 

Truly Democrat corruption at its finest led by Kathy Hochul. 

And as always, Governor Hochul’s refusal to eliminate New York City’s congestion pricing toll—a punishing unaffordable tax opposed by a vast majority of New Yorkers—demonstrates her utter disregard for the financial burdens facing commuters, workers, and small businesses.

The process behind this budget, the latest in 15 years, reeks of cronyism and incompetence. New Yorkers deserve a transparent, fiscally responsible budget that prioritizes our needs, not the desperate attempt to shore up a politically weakened and toxic governor who is desperately trying to shore up her abysmal poll numbers.

As the highest-ranking Republican in New York, I resolutely oppose Hochul's unaffordable plan and will continue fighting to restore commonsense policies that put New Yorkers FIRST. 

Change is coming. And we must work together to SAVE NEW YORK from Hochul’s sheer incompetence and ineptitude.

Name: Suozzi, Thomas R.
text:
Today marks the 80th anniversary of VE Day, or Victory in Europe Day, which commemorates the end of World War II in Europe. On this day, the Allies formally accepted the unconditional surrender of Nazi Germany’s armed forces on May 8, 1945. While the official conclusion of WWII would not be realized until nearly four months later, with Japan's surrender, VE Day provided the world with something it desperately needed: hope.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Over the past four months, Ed Martin has abused his position as interim U.S. Attorney to advance a dangerous agenda that places the president’s personal interests above those of the public, tramples the rule of law, and puts our democracy at risk.

He is unfit to serve in public office. 

That’s why I put a hold on his nomination and made clear I would use every tool at my disposal to oppose his confirmation.

Ed Martin has opened political investigations where there was no evidence to warrant them. He has dismissed cases against his own clients and demonstrated the most profound conflicts of interest. 

He has fired, demoted and forced the resignation of dedicated professionals who refused to go forward with his unethical edicts and those of others in the department. Scrutiny of Martin’s past also exposed his embrace of avowed antisemites, his undisclosed appearances on Russian state media, and his support for violent January 6th insurrectionists.  

Ed Martin is unfit to practice law, let alone serve as a United States Attorney.

I will be watching closely to see whom the President nominates next to serve as the U.S. Attorney for D.C. And I will keep working to ensure that the January 6 deniers are not confirmed to positions from which they can undermine our rule of law and threaten our democracy.

The American people deserve a Justice Department that is devoted to justice.

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
Joyfully, people around the world have learned of a new Pope elected by one of the largest and most diverse conclaves ever — and the first American pope in history.

For many of us, the name Leo XIV happily brings to mind Leo XIII’s Rerum novarum which was a blessing for working people. And it is heartening that His Holiness continued the blessing that Pope Francis gave on Easter Sunday: “God loves everyone. Evil will not prevail.”

In his own words, Pope Leo XIV said, “We can be a missionary church, a church that builds bridges, that is always open to receive everyone.”

Let us thank God for His Holiness Pope Leo XIV and for this vision of unity. All of us hope and pray for the success of His Holiness and his vision for the Church.

text:

Pope Leo has consistently stood with people struggling in poverty, those who are victims of repression, the immigrant community, and those who the governments of the world have forgotten—and I hope he will continue to lead with that same spirit of compassion and global solidarity.

At a time of rising authoritarianism and deepening inequality, the world desperately needs a church that defends the poor, stands up for human rights, and opens its doors to those who’ve long been left out. I pray that Pope Leo will meet this moment with courage, humility, and a commitment to justice.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: 🧵A quick rundown on the first American pope in history: https://t.co/7jUeP84bJP

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Cardinal Robert Francis Prevost, born in Chicago and raised in Dolton, IL, a working-class suburb south of the city, is now Pope Leo XIV. From America to the Vatican — this marks a historic shift for the Catholic Church.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: His choice of the name Leo could be a promising sign of what’s to come. Pope Leo XIII, the most recent pope to hold the name, was no pushover—he stood firm against the tide of socialism. In 1891, he wrote Rerum Novarum, one of the Church’s clearest defenses of family, faith, and free society. He stood up for the truth and warned of the misery that follows collectivist ideology.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: He’s been a consistent defender of the unborn and a strong advocate for the dignity of every human life. He spent years in Peru, ministering in some of the most forgotten corners of the world. Later, he led the global process to appoint bishops, shaping the Church’s leadership.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: Here’s to hoping that Pope Leo leads with moral clarity, courage, and conviction.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text: As many here on X are pointing out, he has voiced disagreement with President Trump and Vice President Vance on issues including the border and deportations. Despite the differences, President Trump issued a statement today congratulating the new pope, calling it “a Great Honor for our Country” and saying he looks forward to “a very meaningful” meeting.

Name: LaLota, Nick
text:
Joint Statement from New York Reps. Elise Stefanik, Andrew Garbarino, Nick LaLota, and Mike Lawler:

We’ve negotiated in good faith on SALT from the start—fighting for the taxpayers we represent in New York.

Yet with no notice or agreement, the Speaker and the House Ways and Means Committee unilaterally proposed a flat $30,000 SALT cap—an amount they already knew would fall short of earning our support.

It’s not just insulting—it risks derailing President Trump’s One Big Beautiful Bill.

New Yorkers already send far more to Washington than we get back—unlike many so-called “low-tax” states that depend heavily on federal largesse.

A higher SALT cap isn’t a luxury. It’s a matter of fairness.

We reject this offer.

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
Grand slam, home run, hat trick pick. 
 
I am beyond pleased with President Trump’s decision to make Jeanine Pirro the interim U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia.
 
She is exactly the right person at the right time to take on this responsibility. She brings to the table wide and deep legal experience combined with a passion for justice and a determination to protect law abiding citizens from criminal predators. 
 
This is exactly what is needed to clean up DC. 
 
With her interim appointment, it is a good day for the law abiding and a bad day for criminals. 

I also hope she will be nominated for the permanent role. If that happens, I believe she will receive - and deserves - overwhelming Republican support and will be confirmed as the next U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia. 
 
Well done Mr. President and congratulations Jeanine.

Emily shared this about her work: “This painting contains two horses standing in a rock bottom creek that has just a little pool of water in it. The horse in front is being led by a rider on the horse in the back. The front horse is splashing in the water while the back horse reaches down for a drink. The left background is covered with brush and trees, the center background is a cliff wall, and the right background you can see more of the rock creek bed and the overhang of tress.”

Thank you to all the talented students from across Southern Illinois who participated and the teachers who support them. Great job, Emily!

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Tamika Jaquetta Farmer, who lives in Williamston, teaches 4th-grade math and science at G.W. Carver Elementary School. During her 12-year career in education, she has worn many hats, including teacher assistant, bus driver, classroom teacher, and mentor. 

As a leader in trauma-informed practices and a member of her school’s resilience team, she helps foster a safe, supportive environment for every student. Her passion for family engagement and community outreach has earned her recognition at every level, including being named the 2025 Edgecombe County Public Schools Teacher of the Year and Burroughs Wellcome Fund North Central Region Teacher of the Year.

She also served honorably in the U.S. Army as a field medic at Fort Bragg, NC. Tamika Jaquetta Farmer is a shining example of strength, grace, and selflessness.

Name: McBath, Lucy
text:
Dr. Carla Hayden is a true trailblazer. She was the first woman and first Black American to serve as the Librarian of Congress, and the first professional librarian to serve in this role since 1974. For nearly a decade, she has worked tirelessly to educate future generations and share the richness of our nation's history-and her work was not yet complete.
 
The President's abrupt firing of Dr. Hayden represents yet another baseless attack on an eminently qualified public servant. I thank Dr. Hayden for her selfless service to the American public and for breaking down barriers for those who will one day follow in her footsteps. My colleagues and I will continue working to defend these assaults on our legislative branch.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we honor members of our community who go above and beyond—who lead with purpose and inspire with action. Today, we shine a spotlight on a young woman whose brilliance, resilience, and heart have made history. Meet this week’s Hometown Hero: @BensalemSchools senior, Victoria Mathieu.
 
At just 18 years old, Tori is blazing a trail—and putting our community on the map. Earlier this month, she became the first Bensalem student ever accepted into five Ivy League universities, part of an extraordinary 14 total college acceptances. Her video capturing the moment went viral—nearly 5 million views—and for good reason. It wasn’t just a celebration of success, but a symbol of what’s possible when hard work, courage, and conviction come together.
 
Beyond her exceptional GPA, Tori has built an academic and service record that speaks volumes. She’s a standout on Bensalem’s Mock Trial Team and founder of her school’s chapter of a global legal honors society. She interned with Legal Aid of Southeastern Pennsylvania, working to expand access to justice for families who too often fall through the cracks. As Co-Chair of the bipartisan Access to Legal Aid Caucus, I know how critical that work is—and the fact that Tori is already leading in this space before she’s even graduated high school is nothing short of extraordinary.
 
Her leadership extends well beyond the classroom. Tori serves as a student representative on the Bensalem School Board, giving her peers a voice in shaping their education. She founded and captains the high school’s Step Dance Team, leads the Reading Olympics Team, and serves as a Pennsylvania Global Ambassador for ReSoap—a youth-led nonprofit combating hygiene poverty and climate change. She’s a proud member of DECA, preparing for a future in business and innovation. And through Still I Shine, the virtual support group she founded, she’s created a space for students across our region to connect, support each other, and feel seen. Tori’s story is a testament to the power of opportunity—and what’s possible when talent is matched by character, conviction, and community values.
 
Her father, Pierre, came to the United States from Haiti at 18. Her mother, Tina, immigrated from Nigeria at 10. Together, they believed in the promise of this country—that through hard work and education, their children could build a better life. Their daughter is living proof of that promise in action. She’s not just walking through doors—she’s holding them open for others.
 
We are incredibly lucky to have a young woman like Victoria Mathieu representing our community. Tori, congratulations on all you’ve achieved—you have an entire community cheering you on! We’re proud. We’re inspired. And we can’t wait to see all that your future holds.

Name: Goodlander, Maggie
text:
Justice David Souter was and always will be a true American hero. 

He was a humble man with a granite backbone who always put our country and our Constitution first. His commitment to common sense was at the heart of his truly uncommon brilliance. And boy did he love New Hampshire — our history, our poets, our mountains and lakes, and, above all, our people. 

Justice Souter understood that every ruling of the United States Supreme Court would change the lives of real people in some meaningful way. That is why he approached his work with a simple and powerful commitment to, as he once put it, "use every power of our minds and our hearts and our beings to get those rulings right."

Justice Souter’s memory will forever be a blessing to me as I work every day to bring every power of my mind, heart, and being to do good for our state and our country.

Name: Stefanik, Elise M.
text:
At my invitation, @America250 came to @FortTiconderoga in New York’s 21st Congressional District to honor the legacy of America’s first victory in the Revolutionary War. The battle for Fort Ticonderoga in 1775 served as the first major victory for the American patriots over the British.

The victory boosted the Continental Army’s morale to continue the fight for liberty and against tyranny, an idea that continues to live in the hearts of all Americans today, as the nation celebrates the 250th anniversary of our founding.

Throughout my time in Congress, I have worked to protect, preserve, improve, and promote New York’s incredible historic sites - particularly our battlefields. I have delivered over millions in funds for Fort Ticonderoga including most recently delivering support for its historic wall reconstruction, a significant investment in preserving our nation’s history.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Law(less) + (Dis)Order(ly) Episode 13

None of these actions make our country safer or citizens more prosperous, but here are some of the things the Trump administration delivered this week:

President Trump threatened to end the program designed to expand high-speed internet access in communities it hasn't yet reached, calling it "woke handouts based on race," despite funding already distributed to red, rural states including Alabama, Iowa, Kansas and Indiana.

One day after testifying in front of Congress to explain why FEMA should not be disbanded, acting administrator Cameron Hilton was summarily fired.

President Trump fired the Librarian of Congress. Carla Hayden was only the 14th person to serve the nation in this apolitical role, and she was also the first woman and first non-white person to do so.

A concept of a trade deal with the United Kingdom, with whom we enjoy a trade surplus, was announced yesterday that will lower the price of Rolls Royce, Bentley, Jaguar, Aston Martin, Range Rover and Mini automobiles. There were no carveouts for any other consumer goods.

The Trump administration is putting pressure on countries facing US tariffs to approve the use of Starlink in their territory, a satellite company owned by special government employee Elon Musk.

President Trump appointed Fox News host Jeanine Pirro to serve as interim US Attorney for the District of Columbia after being forced to withdraw the nomination of his first choice because the "Stop the Steal" activist and J6 defender could not muster the support of the Senate Judiciary Committee.

President Trump pulled down another nominee, this time for Surgeon General, because his first choice came under scrutiny for inflating her credentials. Yesterday he nominated a wellness influencer and author instead.

A vote to make sure the Gulf of Mexico appears as the Gulf of America on US government maps and documents was one of only six bills Speaker Johnson brought to the floor.

Most of the buyers of President Trump's meme coin, who are currently in a competition to win a dinner and/or a special tour with him, have used foreign exchanges that ban US buyers, making it likely that foreigner customers are not only directly enriching the president but also buying access to him.

Pete Hegseth was found to have conducted even more official Pentagon business over the unsecured Signal platform, and yet he is still the Secretary of Defense.

To be continued...

Name: Watson Coleman, Bonnie
text:
At around 1pm today, my colleagues @RepLaMonica @RepMenendez  and I arrived at the Delaney Hall ICE detention facility in Newark to exercise our oversight authority as Members of Congress.

Contrary to a press statement put out by DHS we did not “storm” the detention center. The author of that press release was so unfamiliar with the facts on the ground that they didn’t even correctly count the number of Representatives present. We were exercising our legal oversight function as we have done at the Elizabeth Detention Center without incident.

Reopening Delaney Hall won’t make us safer and it won’t create an immigration system that is fair and secure for all families.

Private Prison companies like GEO Group create a perverse incentive to increase incarceration to increase corporate profits. It’s no accident that GEO Group was the first corporation to max out donations to Trump’s Super PAC, to the tune of $500,000 dollars. And they’re being rewarded with huge contracts to imprison immigrants like we’re seeing here at Delaney.

New Jerseyans don’t want more private prisons just to increase shareholder income at the expense of taxpayers. They want a fair and secure immigration system that reflects our values and respects our Constitution.

Name: Garcia, Sylvia R.
text:
America, this must be our clarion call. We are at risk of backsliding into a dictatorship as Trump continues trying to enact his authoritarian playbook. Republicans and Democrats must stand together against this absurdity. Today it’s Representatives Watson Coleman, Menendez, and McIver. Tomorrow, it’s you. 

Members of Congress are tasked with conducting oversight of the federal government, and these Members were doing just that. I stand with my colleagues who were doing their job and will always stand with those who do the same, regardless of political affiliation.

We must come together and stand up against Trump and his administration’s all-out assault against a co-equal branch of government, the rule of law, and our Constitution. We must all do our part to protect our great American experiment from those who seek to perverse it. We must all make our voices heard against the Trump-Vance administration to ensure we leave a stronger and more resilient democracy for the next generation.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
250 years ago today—before dawn on May 10, 1775—Ethan Allen, Benedict Arnold, and the Green Mountain Boys captured Fort Ticonderoga in America’s first victory of the Revolutionary War.

It wasn’t just a tactical win—it was a turning point. It rallied the cause for liberty, proved the fight was worth waging, and helped shape the legacy of courage, conviction, and self-governance we carry forward to this day.

As part of our #America250 initiative, I’m proud to be leading local efforts to honor that legacy, and the vital role our PA-1 community played in building this nation.

Let’s mark 250 years of freedom, together.

📩 America250@mail.house.gov to get involved.

text:
“All that I am, or hope to be, I owe to my angel mother.” Lincoln’s words ring especially true as I reflect on the extraordinary woman who shaped my life—my mom, Mary Fitzpatrick. She’s the heart of our family, the one who held it all together with quiet strength, deep faith, and unconditional love. Raising eight kids wasn’t easy, but she made it look effortless. She never looked for recognition. She just gave—her time, her energy, her whole self—to everyone around her.

She is the reason I believe in service. The reason I understand commitment. The reason I am who I am.

To my mom—and to every incredible mom across PA-1—thank you. Wishing you a Mother’s Day filled with love, rest, and the appreciation you deserve!

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Join me in congratulating four outstanding young leaders—Andrew Woerz of Troop 27 in Riegelsville, Stephen Shermer of Troop 108 in East Greenville, Maxwell Dumack of Troop 99 in Wrightstown, and Brandon Staehle of Troop 187B in Sellersville, on earning the rank of Eagle Scout, a reflection of their hard work and dedication to service. 

For their scout projects, Andrew designed and built a nature-inspired playground at Windmill Day Camp and School in Doylestown, giving back to the place where his own learning journey began. His project now provides a creative and safe space for future generations to grow and explore.

Stephen created two custom picture frame shelves for the Pennsburg Thrift Store, thoughtfully designed with fabric-lined slots to safely store and organize merchandise. His project improved the store’s functionality and helped support the local families and individuals who rely on it.

Maxwell led the landscaping design, fundraising, and installation of plantings for the FOP Lodge’s Fallen Officer Memorial—a thoughtful, enduring tribute that honors our heroes and brings new beauty and meaning to the space.

Brandon combined his love of history and nature by designing and installing a Historical Storybook Sign at Lenape Park in Perkasie. He researched the park’s landmarks, gathered stories, photographs, and created a visitor-friendly map.

These are the kinds of acts that reflect true leadership and create lasting ripple effects. But behind every Eagle Scout is a foundation of support and sacrifice—a special thank you to the incredible moms of Andrew, Stephen, Maxwell, Brandon, and all our PA-1 Scout moms, whose guidance and encouragement have shaped these young men into the outstanding leaders they’ve become.

Name: Watson Coleman, Bonnie
text: Hi Julio, I see how this is confusing so allow me to clarify. We were admitted into the facility before the mayor’s arrest for our oversight tour. We were not actually given the tour until after. When we were admitted we were put in a holding room in the facility while on-site officials called their superiors to confirm that, by law, they have to give us a tour. While that’s happening, we learn that they are planning to arrest the mayor even though he had already left the premises. So we go back outside to see if this is true, and to speak to the mayor. While we’re speaking to the mayor on the public side of the gate, around 20 armed ICE agents swarm us and shove us and handcuff the mayor, then drag him back inside the gate, which is the scuffle you see on video. Hope this helps clear things up.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Our men and women who serve as law enforcement officers put their lives on the line daily to protect our communities. As we recognize Police Week, we are proud to support the following three bipartisan bills that help those who uphold public safety for all:

▪️H.R. 2240, the Improving Law Enforcement Officer Safety and Wellness Through Data Act, a bill to require the Department of Justice to report on targeted attacks on law enforcement officers, the feasibility of incorporating such attacks into existing crime reporting systems, and the mental health resources available to police.

▪️H.R. 2189, the Law-Enforcement Innovate to De-Escalate Act of 2025, legislation to promote the use of non-lethal and de-escalatory technology in civilian encounters to uphold the law while ensuring safety for all parties involved.

▪️H.R. 1551, the Protect and Serve Act of 2025, legislation to enforce penalties against those who intentionally harm law enforcement officers, including when they are in the line of duty.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
I am appalled by @kajakallas' support for Europe’s failed Political Dialogue and Cooperation Agreement (PDCA) with the Cuban regime. 

Since 2016/2017, the Cuban regime has expanded its repression, imprisoned democracy activists (with many still in prison since the J11 protests of 2021), invited the PRC to establish an extensive spy hub 90 miles from U.S. shores, deepened its military training and weapons relationship with Belarus – all while thousands of Cuban nationals fight in Ukraine for Russia.

The so-called economic “reforms” constitute a handful of business licenses provided to the regime’s cronies; the new “laws” are decrees that will be ignored at whim. And how many of the released political prisoners are back in prison? The truth is that the Cuban people languish under a totalitarian dictatorship with a closed communist economy. The rest is propaganda. Continuing the PDCA, especially with its windfalls of assistance to the regime, enables the status quo at the expense of the Cuban people.

I commend Sweden’s principled leadership in asking for a formal review, my dear friends in Lithuania continuing to stand against ratification, and the courageous parliamentarians who spoke in favor of terminating the PDCA. History and the Cuban people will remember those who stood with them in the struggle for freedom.

@kajakallas, @JohanForssell, @ZygisPavilionis, @Zingeris, @USEmbassyKyiv, @SecRubio

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
President @realDonaldTrump's executive order on prescription drug prices is a major step toward finally bringing fairness to American patients and taxpayers. For too long, Americans have paid far more than those in other countries for the same prescription drugs. In Europe, for example, patients often pay a tenth of what we pay here in the United States. President Trump and his Administration are taking action to change that.
 
Once again, President Trump is showing that his only special interest is the American people—and that’s mine too. By tying what we pay in the U.S. to the lowest prices paid abroad, this executive order is expected to reduce drug costs by as much as 59%. That means real relief for seniors and families across the country. 
 
This action will help increase competition and lower costs across the board for essential prescription drugs. It’s exactly the kind of bold, America-First reform we need to fix our healthcare markets—and I applaud President Trump for taking action to deliver this historic change.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: By a nearly 2-to-1 ratio, more Americans now work in government than in manufacturing. Nearly 50% of our cars, over 60% of our machine tools, 80% of our pharmaceuticals, and almost 90% of the semiconductor chips we need for everything from phones to fighter jets are foreign-made.

Name: Schmitt, Eric

By 2018, Missouri alone had lost an estimated 90,000 manufacturing jobs—more than 25% of our total industrial base.

From my speech: https://t.co/UERLVnepPS

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In the 70s, southeast Missouri was home to as many as 90 shoe plants. The last factory from that era closed for good in 2005. It had begun as a five-story, 92,000-foot factory in Cape Girardeau, nicknamed “the Pride of Southeast Missouri.” At one time, it employed 1,200 workers. https://t.co/ZmUEsgPlQI

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
But cheaper imports from low-wage countries began to flood the market, and by 1990, the old factory was razed and replaced with a one-story plant. By 2001, its workforce had dwindled to just 50.

Here's what one former employee told a local paper after the plant closed for good: https://t.co/13VtWjBVKj

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Tri-Con Industries, which makes car seat parts, shuttered its factory in Cape Girardeau, too, and moved its production to Mexico. That was another 200 jobs gone.

We saw the same pattern, time and time again, across any number of industries. Factories—and towns—simply evaporated. https://t.co/HouoDlS4sP

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: Toastmaster used to make their stuff in Missouri, too. But by 2001, all the plants had been relocated from rural mid-Missouri to China. The last one to go, in the town of Macon—near where I went to school—left a toxic waste cleanup site for the 5500-person town it left behind. https://t.co/TnozwAXfFg

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
I'll give you one more example: The Noranda Aluminum smelter in New Madrid went bankrupt—suffocated by a flood of cheap, state-subsidized Chinese aluminum.

The effects on the town of less 3,000 people were devastating.

"People lost homes," the mayor said. "People got divorced." https://t.co/XDNnmy82Hv

Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
I am very pleased that President Trump is standing up for American consumers when it comes to purchasing prescription drugs.

Under the current system, the United States pays on average three times more for prescription drugs than other developed nations because other countries set price limits on prescription drugs, creating a situation where Americans pay more because pharmaceutical companies are trying to recoup the research and development costs for these medications.

President Trump’s executive order stipulates that American consumers will receive ‘Most-Favored-Nation’ treatment by telling pharmaceutical companies they cannot charge Americans more than they are charging people in other developed nations. This will result in reduced prescription drug prices and will shift the cost of research and development to other countries.

U.S.-based companies conduct more than half of the research and development for all pharmaceutical products, including prescription drugs. It’s time for the rest of the developed world to share in the costs of making that happen, instead of only reaping the benefits of American innovation.

text:
In the middle of the night, House Republicans released the text of Donald Trump's "big, beautiful bill." Despite what they've said for months, it's now confirmed:

They're ripping health care away from millions of Americans to give their billionaire donors another tax cut.🧵

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Republicans are going to talk a lot in the coming days about targeting "waste, fraud and abuse" in Medicaid. But you can't find $715 billion in waste in the program – it simply isn't possible.

What they're really doing is zeroing in on working families. Here's three examples:

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
The nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office found that Trump's bill will eliminate health coverage for at least 13.7 MILLION people.

They're doing this by slashing $715 BILLION from Medicaid and the Affordable Care Act, even though they pledged not to cut Americans' health care.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
First, they're instituting what they call "work requirements." The idea is that if you aren't disabled, you have to work to qualify for Medicaid.

Sounds reasonable, right?

But the reality is that the vast majority of Medicaid recipients are already employed. Seriously! https://t.co/PdlFbulDaW

Name: Markey, Edward J.
text: @ENERGY Secretary Chris Wright’s clean energy cuts and false claims cannot stand. Join me live on the Senate floor. https://t.co/EKYqzjaqI2

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
And we have two examples of Republican-controlled states that tried to implement "work requirements" and failed miserably.

In Arkansas, more than 18,000 people lost coverage because of bureaucratic and paperwork issues.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
In Georgia, just 2% of eligible residents received coverage, and the bulk of the state's spending was used on administrative expenses to implement work reporting instead of health care.

Taking this failed policy nationwide is a disaster.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Second, Republicans have decided that they are the ones who determine whether Americans have "real disabilities" preventing them from working.

Think about that – politicians in Washington making decisions about your health care so they can give a tax break to their donors.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
Third, if you meet the work requirement AND complete all the extra paperwork Republicans are requiring, they're also going to make you pay more for doctor's appointments.

Specifically, if you make more than $15,650 a year, you can expect your co-pays to go up.

Name: Trahan, Lori
text:
I'm still working through the bill that was published late last night, so I'll share more in the coming hours.

But it's important that you know House Republicans are moving fast.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
It was a true honor to join the Nixon High School community in celebrating two outstanding students whose talents and commitment shine brightly: Xerina Noreen Coleman and Gabriel Lerma.

Xerina has been appointed to the United States Naval Academy Preparatory School, a powerful testament to her character, courage, and readiness to serve. Her path is one of leadership and purpose, and we couldn't be prouder.

Gabriel, winner of the 2025 Congressional Art Competition for the 28th District of Texas, reminds us that art is service too. His beautiful piece, “Texas Spirit,” will soon hang in the U.S. Capitol, telling the story of our heritage and heart through color and creativity.

I also had the pleasure of presenting Congressional Certificates of Recognition to other talented Nixon students who submitted artwork for the competition. 

A special thank you to Principal Cassandra Mendoza, Assistant Principals Rebecca Gonzalez and J.J. Solis, Councilman Rick Garza, Ms. Brooke Berrios for fostering student creativity, the families of Xerina and Gabriel for their unwavering support, and Captain Tom Clarity of the Naval Academy Preparatory School for sending words of encouragement.

To Xerina and Gabriel: your journeys may be different, one through service, one through art, but both are filled with promise, purpose, and passion.

Thank you to the families, educators, and community members lifting up our youth. Laredo, the future is bright because of students like these!

Over the last week and a half, my team and I have been working every day to push for the full restoration of airline operations to and from Newark Liberty International Airport.
 
Here’s some of the actions I’ve taken🧵

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text: I’ve talked with everyone--from air traffic controllers to affected travelers. We need an action plan from the administration and the FAA on the steps they are taking to end the daily disruptions and uncertainty at Newark Airport. What is being done to make this right and end the disruptions at one of the world’s largest airports?

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text: The air traffic control center in Philadelphia that is responsible for Newark’s airspace needs to be brought up-to-date, urgently. Newark is a vital hub for people worldwide and it is inexcusable that its air traffic control system has suffered repeated malfunctions for more than two weeks. The administration must make this fix its immediate top priority.

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text:
Secretary Duffy’s press conference today was a start, but the public deserves full transparency into what’s happening.
 
My office has heard from many frustrated travelers – and I’ve heard from my own friends and community. People deserve to know what is going on and what’s being done to fix the problems. The Department of Transportation and FAA need to increase the number of public briefings and provide more details about each incident.

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text: People are not looking for someone to blame, they simply want to know they’ll arrive at their destination safely and on time.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
Last night, House Republicans released their plan to gut Medicaid and the Affordable Care Act — closing hospitals, blowing a hole in state budgets, and ripping away health care from MILLIONS OF PEOPLE.

What happens next? Here’s what you need to know. 🧵

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text: 1. Republicans’ bill would leave millions of people without health insurance. The nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office found that as a result of these cuts to Medicaid and the Affordable Care Act, 13.7 million people would go uninsured — all left one accident or injury away from economic ruin. And we will all pay the price. All so Republicans can give tax breaks to the wealthiest few.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
2. Not only will patients suffer — but so will providers. The bill cuts at least $715 billion in health care funding. Doctors, nurses, hospitals, community health centers and more need that funding to cover the costs of providing care. Without it, providers will have no choice but to drop services or close completely.

We could see a widespread shuttering of hospitals and community health centers, especially in the rural and underserved communities that need them most.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
3. Burdensome paperwork and red tape is designed to keep people from getting health insurance.

Republicans are trying to make it as hard as possible for people to get on Medicaid, in the hopes that this will cut costs. But the uninsured will go to the Emergency Room when they are sickest — and the costs will spread to everyone else’s insurance premiums.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
4. States CANNOT make up the difference in lost federal health care funding, and this bill handcuffs a significant tool they’ve used to pay for Medicaid — the provider tax. Republicans ask states to make the impossible decision of raising taxes or cutting benefits even as they have to make up for cuts in federal funding for education, infrastructure, public safety, housing and more.

As a former state legislator with nearly 18 years of experience in the Virginia General Assembly, I can say with certainty that we are asking more from our state legislatures than they can give.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
5. Any claims that Medicaid subsidizes freeloaders who “choose not to work” and “leech off the government” are complete bogus — and an insult to the millions of Americans who support Medicaid.

Nearly everyone on Medicaid works or is otherwise employed. If they aren’t, there’s a reason. I’ve heard stories across Virginia’s Fourth who turned to Medicaid not out of laziness, but real need. These are taxpayers, home care workers, people with debilitating disabilities or conditions.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
6. House Republicans KNOW what they’re doing is unpopular. It’s why Republicans unveiled this bill under the cover of darkness — literally — to avoid any immediate blowback.

It’s why they avoided admitting for months what the CBO said was true — that they can’t fund their tax cuts without gutting Medicaid.

It’s why their claim that they’re “strengthening” Medicaid couldn’t be further from the truth.

Name: McClellan, Jennifer L.
text:
The fight to save Medicaid has been ongoing for months. It comes to a head tomorrow at 2 PM, when the House Energy and Commerce Committee convenes to mark up Republicans’ health care bill.

From my time as a state legislator to a member of @EnergyCommerce, I’ve stood on the side of expanding access to health care and helping people get the care they need. I have no intention of stopping now.

Name: Elfreth, Sarah
text:
For 200 years, race-based slavery was legal in Maryland. It remains one of the most shameful and painful chapters in the history of the state and our nation. @ChrisVanHollen and I had the distinct honor of gathering at the Whitehall, former plantation and home to the last colonial Governor of Maryland, to meet the descendants who are now leading efforts to preserve and share their ancestors’ stories.

We spoke about their work to ensure the past is not forgotten, and how Congress can support the ongoing efforts to honor those who endured unimaginable cruelty at Whitehall and beyond. Their strength and dedication are a testament to resilience – and a reminder of our responsibility to confront the legacy of slavery with honesty and action. I’m so grateful to the families, organized by my friend Janice Hayes Williams, who joined us for this difficult and important conversation.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
If an asteroid the size of a jet plane was on track to hit Earth in 2032, would we see it in time to stop it?

Earlier this year, that question got uncomfortably real.

Here’s why I’m chairing a hearing this week in @HouseScience about Planetary Defense:

🧵 https://t.co/yVFiuYwxhK

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
In late December, astronomers discovered a new near-Earth object called 2024 YR4, and estimated its size to be between 174 and 220 feet across.

Just weeks later, NASA raised its estimated chance of hitting Earth to 3.1%, a 1-in-32 chance.

That's the highest impact risk they’ve ever recorded for an asteroid of that size.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
The scare revealed two things:

First, the good news: When we detect these objects early, our systems work.

Second, we are still far behind where we need to be when it comes to detection and tracking.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
For several tense weeks, scientists tracked the asteroid and worked to refine its projected orbit. The more observations they gathered, the clearer the path became. 

Fortunately, by late February, NASA reduced the chance of impact to just 0.004%.

This one will miss us. But that might not always be the case.

https://t.co/3NJ4G17ZIQ

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
In 2013, a meteor exploded over Chelyabinsk, Russia, shattering windows across 200 square miles and injuring more than 1,500 people.

That object was roughly 65 feet wide. 2024 YR4 is nearly 3 times larger. 

A strike from something that size could easily destroy a city.

https://t.co/DzxRPfMRAi

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
In 2005, Congress gave NASA a mission: Locate 90% of all near-Earth objects larger than 140 meters by the year 2020.

It’s now 2025, and NASA has found only 44%.

That means thousands of potentially dangerous asteroids are still out there, untracked. https://t.co/GswMHw3MA6

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
NASA also runs advanced simulations that model asteroid threats and help inform how we would respond.

But every model depends on accurate data. Without enough observations, the margin for error grows.

That’s why we need to invest in both detection and response capabilities.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
Thankfully, reality looks a lot more precise.

In 2022, NASA launched the DART mission, which deliberately crashed a spacecraft into an asteroid nearly seven million miles from Earth.

The impact changed the asteroid’s orbit, and proved that redirection is possible.

And yes, we have it on video: https://t.co/KDkYlu9oYx

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
But finding them is only step one.

What happens if we identify an object that’s actually headed for Earth?

If that brings to mind Bruce Willis blowing up an asteroid, you’re not alone. 

The movie Armageddon gave many people their first idea of what planetary defense might look like.

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
Tune in to the hearing Thursday morning at 10:00 AM ET.

We’ll be hearing from top experts at NASA, UCLA, and the Smithsonian Minor Planet Center to ensure that the Earth is ready before the next 2024 YR4 appears.

https://t.co/qzSbiZTp7A

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
This Thursday, I’ll be chairing a @HouseScience Space Subcommittee hearing to review NASA’s Planetary Defense Strategy.

We’ll be asking hard questions: Are we identifying threats fast enough? Do we have the tools to stop them? And what still needs to happen?

https://t.co/7Lo7jtrC2q

Name: Haridopolos, Mike
text:
Planetary defense is not just a scientific exercise or science fiction. It's a matter of emergency preparedness, risk management and national security.

Because when it comes to defending Earth, there are no second chances.

Tune in on Thursday at 10AM.

Few people in Missouri politics have had more of a positive influence on our state and the nation than Senator Kit Bond.

He was a cheerful warrior who always had an encouraging word and a smile on his face, even in challenging times.

https://t.co/rHzsivhysi

Name: Wagner, Ann
text: After leaving elected office, Kit continued to advocate for our state and the policies he fought for throughout his career.  My happiest phone calls in recent memory were from Kit and Linda inviting Ray and me to dinner.  Sharing stories about Missouri politics, both past and present, spanning three decades, was always the highlight of the evening, and something I will miss dearly.

Name: Wagner, Ann
text: At a time when it was hard for women to break into politics, Kit was a forward-thinking visionary who worked to promote and advance the careers of many women entering public service.  I was so honored to serve as Missouri Republican Party Chairman alongside Kit’s incomparable female Chief of Staff Julie Dammann and Speaker of the House Catherine Hanaway, advancing strong conservative policies that benefitted our state.

Name: Wagner, Ann
text: Ray and I are heartbroken to hear of his passing and our prayers are with his wife Linda, who took such incredible care of him and supported him always, as well as his son, Sam, and the entire Bond family.  Kit was a dear friend, a mentor, and I would not be where I am today were it not for his friendship, advice and support.  I will miss him every day.

Name: McClain Delaney, April

May is Mental Health Awareness Month, and it's a reminder that it's okay to not be okay and that help is always within reach. Mental health is health. We wouldn't ignore a broken bone, and we shouldn’t ignore depression, anxiety, or any mental health struggle either.
If you're going through a tough time, please know you're not alone. There are people who care and want to help. You can call or text 988 anytime to reach the Suicide & Crisis Lifeline. It's free, confidential, and available 24/7.
For more resources, or to share your own story, visit the National Alliance on Mental Illness at https://t.co/JRBVlBsLEb or explore their Mental Health Awareness Month page here.
Let’s keep talking about mental health; not just this month, but every day until no one feels like they have to face it alone.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
Over the weekend, firefighters carried out several prescribed burns near Paradise Lake in the Plumas National Forest—an essential tool in keeping our forests healthy and reducing the risk of catastrophic wildfires.

Roughly 50 acres were treated, and the results are right in line with what’s needed: reduced hazardous fuels, improved soil health, and stronger wildlife habitat. Crews from the Plumas and Tahoe National Forests, CAL FIRE, BLM, and the Butte County Fire Safe Council all played a role. Their hard work on the ground helps ensure these burns are effective and safe.

This kind of proactive forest management is exactly what we need more of. Prescribed fire, when done right, at the right time of year, helps return forests to a more natural state and makes them more resilient to future wildfires.

More burns like this, more often, combined with thinning and bringing back industry—that’s how we get ahead of the wildfire crisis in the West.

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
Republicans are planning deep cuts to Medicaid — a lifeline for millions.

In Contra Costa and Solano Counties, 40% of residents rely on Medi-Cal. These cuts would devastate families, especially people with disabilities.

Real people will be hurt. Here are their stories. #NoCutsToMedicaid
🧵

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
2/ Marissa, Vallejo, CA

“My son with down syndrome went into a workability program in Napa and was wrapping soaps for a company that sells soaps in winery gift shops. Our son would always come home happy. He had a high self-esteem, because he was proud to earn money and be productive.

Because of Medicaid’s job coach program, he was able to explore job opportunities that fit his needs. If Medicaid is going away, my son will lose his life, because he will end up not going out and will have nothing to sustain him.”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
3/ Ana, Suisun City, CA

“I’m the conservator and caregiver of two adults with disabilities. They both receive Medi-Cal and Social Security survivor’s benefits. Medicaid allows them to live at home with me as their care provider. My niece is 46 years old. She has lived with me for 23 years - after her mother died from breast cancer. My son is 24 years old and autistic. They are both non-verbal, and my niece is non-ambulatory.

They are each enrolled in day programs and have recreational and social activities through the regional center. We have learned to live within our means, however, cuts to Medi-Cal or in-home care would be devastating to our household.”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
5/ Wardine, Fairfield, CA

“I got injured and I’ve had four back surgeries. I rely on Medicaid and Medicare. I take medication every day. Without Medicaid, I won’t be able to afford it. I don’t know what I’m gonna do. I am 100% disabled. I am devastated and scared of the horrible things that are happening in the United States.”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
4/ Iris, Richmond, CA

“Tengo una hija con autismo, que recibe servicios de Medi-Cal, al recortar fondos, mi hija quedaría sin estos servicios y nosotros no podemos pagar, somos una familia de 6 con un solo ingreso, lo que implicaría un retrazo en el desarrollo de mi hija. Por favor no hagan estos recortes, ya que muchas familias como la mía quedaríamos en riesgo de no recibir más estos servicios que son vitales para nuestros seres queridos. De antemano muchisimas gracias por considerar mi petición.”

Translation: “I have a daughter with autism, who receives services from Medi-Cal. By cutting funds, my daughter would be left without these services and we cannot afford to pay. We are a family of six with a single income, which would mean a delay in my daughter's development. Please do not make these cuts, as many families like mine would be at risk of no longer receiving these services that are vital for our loved ones. Thank you very much in advance for considering my request.”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
7/ Angel, Vacaville, CA

“My severely disabled son 16 years old has a profound intellectual disability, and significantly aggressive behavior. He would be sent to a residential program for youth with extreme behavior needs if our services were cut.

Currently, he requires my husband to be his main caregiver who quit his career to be my son’s caregiver. I work full time as an administrator supporting families with students with special needs. Without Medi-Cal, it would cost us thousands of dollars to put him in a full time living and educational program, and the extra fees for therapies would drown us.”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
6/ Martha, Vallejo, CA

“I’m a Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW) who works with families and caregivers who have had their babies in the neonatal intensive care unit (NICU). I support families secure their baby and families’ medical health insurance which about 95% of the time is Medi-Cal.

If Medicaid was cut, the lives of the babies and their families would be profoundly negatively impacted. They will become incredibly stressed and financially overwhelmed. This is just the tip of the iceberg!”

Name: Garamendi, John
text:
End/

Trump and House Republicans proposed $715 billion Medicaid budget cut would devastate families.

I’ll keep fighting like hell to protect Solano and Contra Costa families from these dangerous cuts.

Thanks @CalSCDD for your support.

Name: Whitesides, George
text:
1) There is a lot of national news coming out every single day, but we can’t lose sight of the upcoming budget fight because the stakes couldn’t be higher.

This week, Congressional Republicans are unveiling their budget framework for the next decade, and we recently got our first look at the one coming out of the Energy and Commerce Committee. Here's what it says:

Name: Whitesides, George
text: 2) One of the most devastating elements of this bill is the proposed cuts to Medicaid. If this budget plan were to pass, it would leave an estimated 1.5 million adults without health insurance across the US, and would threaten the coverage of over 240,000 people in our district who rely on this program for health care.

Name: Whitesides, George
text:
5) Another part of the proposed cuts target assistance for homeowners who install energy-saving and efficient appliances or systems. 

This assistance allows individuals and families, especially those with lower incomes, to reduce their energy bills and lower their environmental impact.

Name: Whitesides, George
text:
4) Along with these cuts, the budget would penalize organizations that work with Planned Parenthood and provide reproductive health care.

This would deny patients access to essential healthcare services like birth control, STI testing and treatment, wellness exams, and more.

Name: Whitesides, George
text:
3) Through unfair cuts in Supplemental Security Income (SSI) benefits for disabled children in low-income families, it would be even harder for these families to make ends meet.

Roughly one-third of families with children receiving SSI already live below the poverty line. SSI benefits help them afford basic needs like food and housing as well as disability-related expenses like therapies or home modifications, which health insurance often doesn’t cover.

Name: Whitesides, George
text: 7) Read more here: https://t.co/fKFzXnrlYx

Name: Whitesides, George
text: 6) We will learn a lot more over the coming week about the real harms posed by these budgets, and how we can best fight for families across our districts. The fact that we are even having a conversation about cutting health care, food assistance, and basic needs is completely unacceptable.

Name: Stefanik, Elise M.
text:
BIG NEWS for Saratoga & American History! I successfully championed a bill through the House to rename Saratoga National Historical Park to Saratoga National Battlefield Park!

Why does this matter to our community? Because this battlefield — right here in our own backyard — marks the site where history changed forever. The Battles of Saratoga were the turning point in the American Revolution, where a British army surrendered for the first time. It's more than a park — it's a symbol of resilience, sacrifice, and the roots of our independence.

With overwhelming local support and a unanimous push from the Saratoga County Board of Supervisors, this redesignation restores the historical identity of this sacred ground as we approach the 250th anniversary of the battles that helped forge our nation.
